{"title_page": "Thomas Crisp (MP)", "text_new": "'''Thomas Crisp'''  (c. 1690\u20131758), of Parbold, near Wigan, Lancashire, was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1727 to 1734.\n\nCrisp was the eldest son of William Crisp of Parbold and his wife Isabella. In 1704, he succeeded his father. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]]  in  1709. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/crisp-thomas-1690-1758| title=CRISP, Thomas (c.1690-1758), of Parbold, nr. Wigan, Lancs. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nCrisp  was recommended to be [[High Sheriff of Lancashire]] in 1715 as \u2018a person of known affection to his Majesty and his government\u2019. The Jacobite rebellion occurred during his term of office, and in 1716 and 1717 he petitioned the Treasury for compensation for loss of the sheriff's profits as a result. He was awarded \u00a31,284 in repayment, together with an extra \u00a3475 for his extraordinary care, pains and diligence in  discharging his office of sheriff.  At the [[1722 British general election]]  he was considered as a candidate for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]], but withdrew before the election.   He was returned as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilchester]] at the [[1727 British general election]]. He voted with the Administration on the civil list arrears in 1729, on the Hessians in 1730 and on the army in 1732. He then voted with the Opposition on the excise bill in 1733 and the repeal of the Septennial Act in 1734. He was defeated at Ilchester at the  [[1734 British general election]]  and did not stand again.<ref name=HOP/> \n\nCrisp married Mary in about 1738. He was the probable builder of Parbold Hall.<ref>[https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1278311 Historic England \u2013 Parbold Hall]</ref> He died on 3 April 1758, aged 68, leaving a son and daughter,<ref name=HOP/> Mary, who married Sir John Tyrrell 5th Baronet. \n \n==External links==\n*[https://www.countrylife.co.uk/out-and-about/theatre-film-music/parbold-hall-lancashire-2579 Country Life \u2013 Parbold Hall, Lancashire]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Thomas Paget (died 1741)|Thomas Paget]]\n | before2 = [[Daniel Moore (Ilchester MP)|Daniel Moore]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilchester]]\n | years =   [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[Charles Lockyer]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Charles Lockyer]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Robert Brown, 1st Baronet, of Westminster|Sir Robert Brown]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crisp, Thomas }}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1758 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Crisp'''  (c. 1690\u20131758), of Parbold, near Wigan, Lancashire, was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1727 to 1734.\n\nCrisp was the eldest son of William Crisp of Parbold and his wife Isabella. In 1704, he succeeded his father. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]]  in  1709. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/crisp-thomas-1690-1758| title=CRISP, Thomas (c.1690-1758), of Parbold, nr. Wigan, Lancs. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nCrisp  was recommended to be [[High Sheriff of Lancashire]] in 1715 as \u2018a person of known affection to his Majesty and his government\u2019. The Jacobite rebellion occurred during his term of office, and in 1716 and 1717 he petitioned the Treasury for compensation for loss of the sheriff\u2019s profits as a result. He was awarded \u00a31,284 in repayment, together with an extra \u00a3475 for his extraordinary care, pains and diligence in  discharging his office of sheriff.  At the [[1722 British general election]]  he was considered as a candidate for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]], but withdrew before the election.   He was returned as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilchester]] at the [[1727 British general election]]. He voted with the Administration on the civil list arrears in 1729, on the Hessians in 1730 and on the army in 1732. He then voted with the Opposition on the excise bill in 1733 and the repeal of the Septennial Act in 1734. He was defeated at Ilchester at the  [[1734 British general election]]  and did not stand again.<ref name=HOP/> \n\nCrisp married Mary in about 1738. He was the probable builder of Parbold Hall.<ref>[https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1278311 Historic England \u2013 Parbold Hall]</ref> He died on 3 April 1758, aged 68, leaving a son and daughter,<ref name=HOP/> Mary, who married Sir John Tyrrell 5th Baronet. \n \n==External links==\n*[https://www.countrylife.co.uk/out-and-about/theatre-film-music/parbold-hall-lancashire-2579 Country Life \u2013 Parbold Hall, Lancashire]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Thomas Paget (died 1741)|Thomas Paget]]\n | before2 = [[Daniel Moore (Ilchester MP)|Daniel Moore]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilchester (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilchester]]\n | years =   [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[Charles Lockyer]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Charles Lockyer]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Robert Brown, 1st Baronet, of Westminster|Sir Robert Brown]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crisp, Thomas }}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1758 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of 