{"title_page": "Moneymore, New Zealand", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Moneymore''' is a small farming community in [[South Otago]], [[New Zealand]]. It is located 5 kilometres to the southwest of [[Milton, New Zealand|Milton]], to the south of [[New Zealand State Highway 1|SH 1]].<ref>Dowling, P. (ed.) (2004). \u2019\u2019Reed New Zealand atlas\u2019\u2019. Auckland: Reed Publishing. Map 111. {{ISBN|0 7900 0952 8}}</ref>\n\nOther than farming on the fertile ground of the [[Tokomairaro Plain]], the Moneymore area also has a history of [[coal mining]], associated with the nearby [[lignite]] field at [[Kaitangata, New Zealand|Kaitangata]].<ref>''Wise's New Zealand guide'' (1969) Dunedin: H. Wise & Co. p. 188.</ref>\n\nThe farming area was founded by Edward Martin in 1852, who founded Moneymore Farm, named for his birthplace in [[Moneymore]], [[County Londonderry]]. At the time, the area was simply known as South Toko, but was formally renamed Moneymore in 1902.<ref>[[Alexander Wyclif Reed|Reed, A.W.]] (1975). ''Place names of New Zealand''. Wellington: A.H. & A.W. Reed. pp. 271\u2013272.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|46|09|30|S|169|54|15|E|region:NZ_type:city|display=title}}\n{{Clutha District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Otago]]\n\n\n{{Otago-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Moneymore''' is a small farming community in [[South Otago]], [[New Zealand]]. It is located 5 kilometres to the southwest of [[Milton, New Zealand|Milton]], to the south of [[New Zealand State Highway 1|SH 1]].<ref>Dowling, P. (ed.) (2004). \u2019\u2019Reed New Zealand atlas\u2019\u2019. Auckland: Reed Publishing. Map 111. {{ISBN|0 7900 0952 8}}</ref>\n\nOther than farming on the fertile ground of the [[Tokomairaro Plain]], the Moneymore area also has a history of [[coal mining]], associated with the nearby [[lignite]] field at [[Kaitangata, New Zealand|Kaitangata]].<ref>''Wise's New Zealand guide'' (1969) Dunedin: H. Wise & Co. p. 188.</ref>\n\nThe farming area was founded by Edward Martin in 1852, who founded Moneymore Farm, named for his birthplace in [[Moneymore]], [[County Londonderry]]. At the time, the area was simply known as South Toko, but was formally renamed Moneymore in 1902.<ref>[[Alexander Wyclif Reed|Reed, A.W.]] (1975). ''Place names of New Zealand''. Wellington: A.H. & A.W. Reed. pp. 271\u20132.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|46|09|30|S|169|54|15|E|region:NZ_type:city|display=title}}\n{{Clutha District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Otago]]\n{{Otago-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript& MOS-compliance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moneymore,_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Cicely Tyson", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Cicely Tyson\n| image              = Cicely Tyson.jpg\n| caption            = Tyson in 1997\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1924|12|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Harlem]], [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Kenneth Franklin|1942|}}<ref>https://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?indiv=1&dbid=61788&h=90384728&tid=&pid=&usePUB=true&_phsrc=Pta203&_phstart=successSource</ref> divorce date unknown\n{{Marriage|[[Miles Davis]]|1981|1989|end=div}}\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1949\u2013present\n| notable_works      = {{unbulleted list | ''[[Sounder (film)|Sounder]]'' (1972) | ''[[The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman (film)|The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman]]'' (1974) | ''[[Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All (film)|Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All]]'' (1994) | ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]'' (2011) | ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]'' (2015\u20132020)}}\n}}\n\n'''Cicely L. Tyson''' (born December 19, 1924) is an American [[actress]] and former [[fashion model]]. In a career spanning more than seven decades, she became known for her portrayal of strong [[African-American women]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Cicely-Tyson|title=Cicely Tyson|work=[[Britannica]]|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/top-lists/cicely-tyson-legendary-portrait-of-beauty-courage-and-strength/|title=Cicely Tyson: Legendary Portrait Of Beauty, Courage And Strength|work=CBS Sacramento|last=Melton|first=Lori|date=December 7, 2015|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Tyson is the recipient of three [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], four [[Black Reel Awards]], one [[Screen Actor Guild Award]], one [[Tony Awards|Tony Award]] and an [[Academy Honorary Award|honorary Academy Award]].\n\nHaving appeared in minor film and television roles early in her career, Tyson garnered widespread attention and critical acclaim for her performance as Rebecca Morgan in ''[[Sounder (film)|Sounder]]'' (1972); she was nominated for both the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Motion Picture, Drama|Golden Globe Award]] for Best Actress for her work in the film. Tyson's portrayal of the title role in the 1974 television film ''[[The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman (film)|The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman]]'' won her further praise; among other accolades, the role won her two Emmy Awards and a nomination for a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]].\n\nTyson has continued to act in film and on television in the 21st century. In 2011, she played the role of Constantine Jefferson in the award-winning film ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]''. She has also played the role of Ophelia Harkness in [[American Broadcasting Company]]'s legal drama ''[[How to Get Away With Murder]]'' since the show's inception in 2014, for which she was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]] four times.\n\nIn addition to her screen career, Tyson has appeared in various theater productions. She received a [[Drama Desk Award]] in 1962 for her Off-Broadway performance in ''[[Moon on a Rainbow Shawl]]''. Tyson also starred as Carrie Watts in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] play ''[[The Trip to Bountiful (play)|The Trip to Bountiful]]'', winning the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Tony Award]], the [[Outer Critics Circle Award|Outer Critics Award]], and the [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play|Drama Desk Award for Best Actress in a Play]] in 2013.\n\nTyson was named a [[Kennedy Center Honors|Kennedy Center honoree]] in 2015. In November 2016, Tyson received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], which is the highest civilian honor in the United States.\n\n==Early life==\nTyson was born in [[Harlem]] on December 19, 1924,<ref name=\"ancestry\">{{cite web|title=New York, Naturalization Records, 1882-1944 (database online)|url=http://search.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=2499|publisher=Ancestry.com. Original source: The National Archives and Records Administration (NARA), Washington, D.C.; Petitions for Naturalization from the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, 1897-1944; Series M1972, Roll 956|accessdate=February 22, 2015|ref=In the matter of the petition of William Augustine Tyson to be admitted to become a citizen of the United States of America, Petition No. 248743 (S.D.N.Y., Jul. 31, 1935; granted January 27, 1936)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cicely Tyson Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/cicely-tyson-9512950|publisher=biography.com|accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref> the daughter of Frederica Tyson, a domestic worker, and William Augustine Tyson, who worked as a carpenter, painter, and at any other jobs he could find. Her parents were African-American migrants from Louisiana who fled to the north during the Great Migration..<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/3/Cicely-Tyson.html Cicely Tyson profile], Filmreference.com; retrieved 2013-08-09.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121106104318/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67858566.html CICELY TYSON: BAH, HUMBUG? ACTRESS STARS AS MS. SCROOGE.(LIVING)]. ''The Cincinnati Post'', November 28, 1997.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/10/01/archives/cicely-the-looker-from-sounder-cicely-the-looker.html|work=The New York Times|title=Cicely, the Looker From 'Sounder'; Cicely, the Looker|date=1972-10-01|accessdate=2010-04-30|first=Judy|last=Klemesrud}}</ref> \n==Career==\n===Early work===\n[[File:Cicely Tyson 1973.jpg|thumb|Tyson in 1973]]\nTyson was discovered by a photographer for [[Ebony (magazine)|''Ebony'']] magazine and became a popular fashion model. Her first acting role was on the NBC series ''Frontiers of Faith'' in 1951. Tyson played her first stage role in 1950 and her first film role in ''[[Carib Gold]]'' in 1956, but she went on to do more television work, such as the celebrated series ''[[East Side/West Side]]'', in which she became the first African American to star in a television drama,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cicely Tyson Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/people/cicely-tyson-9512950 |website=Biography |publisher=A&E Television Networks |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> and the soap opera ''[[The Guiding Light]]''.\n\nIn 1961, Tyson appeared in the original cast of French playwright [[Jean Genet]]'s ''[[The Blacks (play)|The Blacks]]'', the longest running off-Broadway non-musical of the decade, running for 1,408 performances.  On March 25, 1963, Tyson appeared on the game show [[To Tell the Truth|To Tell The Truth]] as a decoy contestant for [[Shirley Abicair]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001807/|title=Cicely Tyson|website=IMDb|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> She appeared with [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] in the film ''[[A Man Called Adam (film)|A Man Called Adam]]'' (1966) and starred in the film version of [[Graham Greene]]'s ''[[The Comedians (novel)|The Comedians]]'' (1967). Tyson had a featured role in ''[[The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter (film)|The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter]]'' (1968), and appeared in a  segment of ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Roots'': IMDB cast and crew|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075572/fullcredits|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Stardom===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\nIn 1972, Tyson played the role of Rebecca Morgan in the critically acclaimed  film ''[[Sounder (film)|Sounder]]''. She was nominated for both the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Motion Picture, Drama|Golden Globe Award]] for Best Actress for her work in ''Sounder'', and also won the [[National ociety of Film Critics Award for Best Actress|NSFC Best Actress]] and [[National Board of Review Award for Best Actress|NBR Best Actress]] Awards.\n\nIn 1974, Tyson played the title role in the television film ''[[The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman (film)|The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman]]''. Tyson's portrayal of a young black slave won her a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie and an Emmy Award for Actress of the Year \u2013 Special. Tyson was also nominated for a BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role for her work in this television film.\n\nTyson's acclaimed television roles include: Binta in the 1977 miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]; [[Coretta Scott King]] in the 1978 miniseries ''[[King (miniseries)|King]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]; [[Marva Collins]] in the 1981 television film ''[[The Marva Collins Story]]'', for which she received an [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Television Movie, Mini-Series or Dramatic Special]] and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]], and Muriel in the 1986 television film ''Samaritan: The Mitch Snyder Story'', for which she received an [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Television Movie, Mini-Series or Dramatic Special]].\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1991, Tyson appeared in ''[[Fried Green Tomatoes (film)|Fried Green Tomatoes]]'' as Sipsey.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} In the 1994\u201395 television series ''[[Sweet Justice]]'', Tyson portrayed a civil rights activist and attorney named Carrie Grace Battle, a character she shaped by reportedly consulting with noted [[Washington, D.C.]] civil rights and criminal defense lawyer [[Dovey Johnson Roundtree]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} Other notable film roles include the dramas ''[[Hoodlum (film)|Hoodlum]]'' (1997) and ''[[Diary of a Mad Black Woman]]'' (2005), and the television films ''[[Oldest Living Confederate Widow Tells All]]'' (1994) (for which she received her third Emmy Award) and ''[[A Lesson Before Dying]]'' (1999).{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} In 2005, Tyson co-starred in ''[[Because of Winn-Dixie]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn 2010, Tyson appeared in ''[[Why Did I Get Married Too?]]'' and narrated the [[Paul Robeson|Paul Robeson Award]]-winning documentary, ''Up from the Bottoms: The Search for the American Dream''. In 2011, Tyson appeared in her first music video in [[Willow Smith]]'s ''21st Century Girl''. That same year, she played Constantine Jefferson, a maid in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], in the critically acclaimed period drama ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Help''|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1454029/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_4|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref> Set in the backdrop of the [[Civil Rights Movement]], the film won the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Acting Ensemble]] and the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAt the [[67th Tony Awards]] on June 9, 2013, Tyson won the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play]] for her performance as Miss Carrie Watts in ''[[The Trip to Bountiful (play)|The Trip to Bountiful]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178918-Kinky-Boots-Vanya-and-Sonia-Pippin-and-Virginia-Woolf-Are-Big-Winners-at-67th-Annual-Tony-Awards|title=Kinky Boots, Vanya and Sonia, Pippin and Virginia Woolf? Are Big Winners at 67th Annual Tony Awards|accessdate=2013-06-10|date=2013-06-09|work=[[Playbill]]|author=Purcell, Carey|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611034933/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178918-Kinky-Boots-Vanya-and-Sonia-Pippin-and-Virginia-Woolf-Are-Big-Winners-at-67th-Annual-Tony-Awards|archivedate=2013-06-11}}</ref> She also won the [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play]] and the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Outstanding Actress in a Play for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178137-Billy-Porter-Andrea-Martin-Pippin-Matilda-Vanya-and-Sonia-Win-Drama-Desk-Awards|title=Billy Porter, Andrea Martin, Pippin, Matilda, Vanya and Sonia Win Drama Desk Awards|accessdate=2013-05-20|date=2013-05-19|work=Playbill|author=Hetrick, Adam|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605004524/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/178137-Billy-Porter-Andrea-Martin-Pippin-Matilda-Vanya-and-Sonia-Win-Drama-Desk-Awards|archivedate=2013-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/pippin-is-big-winner-of-2012-13-outer-critics-circle-awards-204640|title=Pippin Is Big Winner of 2012\u201313 Outer Critics Circle Awards|accessdate=May 13, 2013|date=May 13, 2013|work=[[Playbill]]|author=Gans, Andrew}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Tyson played a supporting role in the horror film ''[[The Haunting in Connecticut 2: Ghosts of Georgia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/director-tom-elkins-awakening-the-ghosts-of-georgia/|work=[[Fangoria]]|title=Director Tom Elkins: Awakening the \"GHOSTS OF GEORGIA\"|date=January 3, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2017|author=Staff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301093042/http://www.fangoria.com/new/director-tom-elkins-awakening-the-ghosts-of-georgia/|archive-date=March 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Since 2014, Tyson has guest-starred in ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]'' as Ophelia Harkness, the mother of main character [[Annalise Keating]] ([[Viola Davis]]); for this role, she was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]] in 2015, 2017 and 2018.In 2020 she was in the popular movie A Fall From Grace featured on Netflix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/81127902|title=A Fall from Grace {{!}} Netflix Official Site|website=www.netflix.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nIn addition to her Screen Actor Guild Award, her Tony Award, her Emmy Awards, and her Black Reel Awards, Tyson has received several other honors.\n\nTyson has received honorary degrees from Clark Atlanta University, [[Columbia University]];<ref>[http://news.columbia.edu/oncampus/3464 Honorary degree bestowed on Cicely Tyson] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625160713/http://news.columbia.edu/oncampus/3464 |date=2015-06-25 }}, news.columbia.edu; accessed 3 June 2015.</ref> [[Howard University]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wschronicle.com/2016/05/president-obama-draws-rock-star-reactions-howard-university-commencement/|title=President Obama draws rock-star reactions at Howard University commencement|work=The Chronicle (Winston-Salem)|last=Cox|first=Timothy|date=May 19, 2016|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> and [[Morehouse College]], an all-male [[Historically black colleges and universities|historically black college]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.morehouse.edu/communications/releases/archives/002081.html|title=Morehouse College|website=www.morehouse.edu|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, Tyson was inducted into the [[Black Filmmakers Hall of Fame]]. In 1982, Tyson was awarded the [[Women in Film Los Angeles|Women in Film]] [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards#THE CRYSTAL AWARD|Crystal Award]]. The award is given to outstanding women who, through their endurance and the excellence of their work, have helped to expand the role of women within the entertainment industry.<ref>[http://wif.org/past-recipients Women in Film website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630083646/http://www.wif.org/past-recipients |date=2011-06-30 }}. Wif.org; retrieved 2013-08-09.</ref> In 1988, Tyson received a [[Candace Award]] for Distinguished Service from the [[National Coalition of 100 Black Women]].<ref name=\"page3\">{{cite web |website=National Coalition of 100 Black Women|title=CANDACE AWARD RECIPIENTS 1982-1990, Page 3|url=http://www.ncbw.org/programs/award3.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030314213306/http://www.ncbw.org/programs/award3.html|archivedate=March 14, 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cicely Tyson at The Heart Truth 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Tyson in 2009]]\nIn 2005, Tyson was honored at [[Oprah Winfrey's Legends Ball]]. She has also been honored by the [[Congress of Racial Equality]], the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]], and the [[National Council of Negro Women]].\n\nThe [[Cicely Tyson School of Performing and Fine Arts]], a magnet school in [[East Orange, New Jersey]], was named after her in 2009.<ref>https://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2009/09/cicely_tyson_comes_to_east_ora.html</ref>\n\nTyson was awarded the [[NAACP]]'s 2010 [[Spingarn Medal]] for her contribution to the entertainment industry, her modeling career, and her support of civil rights.<ref>[http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners NAACP Spingarn Medal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707184346/http://www.naacp.org/pages/spingarn-medal-winners |date=2010-07-07 }}. Naacp.org; retrieved 2013-08-09.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.naacp.org/news/entry/naacp-names-cicely-tyson-95th-spingarn-medalist|title=NAACP Names Cicely Tyson 95th Spingarn Medalist|website=www.naacp.org|access-date=2016-03-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20110717230707/http://www.naacp.org/news/entry/naacp-names-cicely-tyson-95th-spingarn-medalist|archivedate=2011-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politic365.com/2010/07/16/naacp-honors-cicely-tyson-with-spingarn-medal-wraps-up-convention/|title=NAACP Honors Cicely Tyson with Spingarn Medal, Wraps Up Convention Politic365|last=Outten|first=Bridgette|access-date=2016-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308165837/http://politic365.com/2010/07/16/naacp-honors-cicely-tyson-with-spingarn-medal-wraps-up-convention/|archive-date=2016-03-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTyson was a recipient of the prestigious [[Kennedy Center Honors]] in 2015.<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Cicely-Tyson|title=Cicely Tyson|work=[[Britannica]]|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> She was awarded the United States' highest civilian honor, the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], by President Barack Obama in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/11/16/502347068/these-are-the-21-people-receiving-the-nations-highest-civilian-honor|title=These Are The 21 People Receiving The Nation's Highest Civilian Honor|date=November 16, 2016|work=[[NPR]]|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences announced that Tyson would receive an [[Academy Honorary Award|honorary Academy Award]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/f9597356bdeb4b4d8a1602b4ec4ec8c6|title=Cicely Tyson, Kathleen Kennedy among film academy honorees|work=APNews.com|last=Bahr|first=Lindsay|date=September 5, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> On November 18, 2018, Tyson became the first African-American woman to receive an honorary Oscar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/awards/2018/11/19/governors-awards-2018-cicely-tyson-kathleen-kennedy/|title=Cicely Tyson, Kathleen Kennedy break new ground with honorary Oscars|work=EW.com|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Tyson was inducted into the [[American Theater Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/cicely-tyson-christine-baranski-david-henry-hwang-more-inducted-into-theater-hall-of-fame-november-12|title=Cicely Tyson, Christine Baranski, David Henry Hwang, More Inducted Into Theater Hall of Fame November 12|publisher=Playbill|date=November 12, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> She was chosen to be inducted into the [[Television Hall of Fame|Television Academy's Hall of Fame]] in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/2c89f44162e08106798cda54831232c4|title=Cicely Tyson, Seth MacFarlane joining TV Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=December 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Miles Davis and Cicely Tyson 1982.jpg|thumb|right|Davis and Tyson, 1982]]\nTyson first dated [[jazz]] [[trumpeter]] [[Miles Davis]] in the 1960s, while he was going through his divorce with dancer [[Frances Taylor Davis|Frances Davis]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 15, 1968|title=Miles Davis And Wife Now 'Miles Apart'|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LrgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=cicely+tyson+miles+davis+jet+1968&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiysv3E2rnmAhWNVc0KHZ3gCnsQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=cicely%20tyson%20miles%20davis%20jet%201968&f=false|journal=Jet|volume= 33| issue =  19|pages=23|via=}}</ref> Davis used a photo of Tyson for his 1967 album, ''[[Sorcerer (Miles Davis album)|Sorcerer]]''. Davis told the press in 1967 that he intended to marry Tyson in March 1968 after his divorce was finalized,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 2, 1967|title=Miles Davis To Make March Merger With Cicely Tyson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7gDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA56&dq=cicely+tyson+miles+davis+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjw3OOYjLnmAhWPVN8KHaP4BdgQ6AEwAnoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=cicely%20tyson%20miles%20davis%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume= 33| issue =  4|pages=56|via=}}</ref> but he married singer Betty Davis that September.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title='One Of Sexiest Men Alive'|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hTgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA48&dq=betty+davis+miles+davis+jet+1968&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6_d7Qz7nmAhXPWc0KHQfUC0wQ6AEwAHoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=betty%20davis%20miles%20davis%20jet%201968&f=false|journal=Jet|volume= 35| issue =  2|pages=48|via=}}</ref> Tyson and Davis rekindled their relationship in 1978. They were married on November 26, 1981 in a ceremony conducted by Atlanta mayor [[Andrew Young]] at the home of actor [[Bill Cosby]]. Their marriage was tumultuous due to Davis' volatile temper and [[infidelity]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Miles: The Autobiography|author1=Davis, Miles|author2=Troupe, Quincy|publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=1990|isbn=978-0-671-72582-2|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/milesautobiograp0000davi}}</ref> Davis credited Tyson with saving his life and helping him overcome his [[cocaine]] addiction.<ref name=\":0\" /> They resided in [[Malibu, California]] and New York City, until she filed for divorce in 1988.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 22, 1988|title=Cicely Tyson To Divorce Trumpeter Miles Davis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gbsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=cicely+tyson+miles+davis+jet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibkpju3rnmAhWaBs0KHQFyD_wQ6AEwA3oECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=cicely%20tyson%20miles%20davis%20jet&f=false|journal=Jet|volume= 73| issue =  21|pages=13|via=}}</ref> Their [[divorce]] was finalized in 1989, two years before Davis died in 1991.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTyson has no children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-cm-ca-cicely-tyson-20140921-story.html|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Cicely Tyson makes a trip that is 'Bountiful' indeed|first=David|last=Ng|date=September 20, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Delta Sigma Theta]] sorority.<ref>https://www.ebony.com/news/delta-sigma-theta-sorority-celebrates-centennial-981/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1956\n|''[[Carib Gold]]''\n|Dottie\n|\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Odds Against Tomorrow]]''\n|Jazz Club bartender\n|\n|-\n|1959\n|''{{sortname|The|Last Angry Man}}''\n|Girl Left on Porch\n|(uncr