{"title_page": "Philip Champion de Crespigny", "text_new": "'''Philip Champion de Crespigny''' (1738\u20131803) was a British lawyer and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1774 and 1790.\n \nHe was of [[Huguenot]] descent, the son of Philip Champion de Crespigny (1704-1765), [[proctor]] of the [[Admiralty court]], and his wife Anne Fonnereau, daughter of [[Claude Fonnereau]] of [[Christchurch Mansion]] in [[Ipswich]], [[Suffolk]]. His elder brother Claude was made a [[Champion de Crespigny baronets|baronet]] in 1805.\n\nPhilip Champion de Crespigny was probably educated at [[Eton College]] in 1748, and was an advocate of [[Doctors' Commons]] in 1759. In 1768 he became [[Government Legal Department|King's Proctor]] and held the post until 1784.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/crespigny-philip-champion-1803| title=\nCRESPIGNY, Philip Champion (d.1803), of Burwood, nr. Cobham, Surr.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1774 British general election|1774]] he was elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]] on the [[Thomas Fonnereau|Fonnereau]] interest after a contest, but lost his seat on petition. In [[1780 British general election|1780]] he was returned unopposed at [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]], also on the Fonnereau interest, as well as at Sudbury after a contest. He held both seats until 1781, when he lost Sudbury on petition, and continued to sit for Aldeburgh. The ''[[English Chronicle]]'' wrote in 1781 that \u201chis hauteur is so distinguished, that he is generally characterised ... by the profane, though very applicable appellation, of God Almighty\u201d. He was returned unopposed at Aldeburgh in [[1784 British general election|1784]], but did not stand in the [[1790 British general election|1790]] election.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nChampion de Crespigny was married four times: first, to Sarah, daughter of Thomas Cocksedge of [[Thetford]], [[Norfolk]], on 24 November 1762; second, about 1771 to Betsy Hodges who died 1772; third to Clarissa, daughter of James Brooke, on 1 July 1774 (she died on 15 May 1782); and fourth, to Dorothy, daughter of Richard Scott of [[Betton, Shropshire|Betton]], [[Shropshire]], on 20 February 1783. He died on 1 January 1803. His obituary in ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]'' described him as \u201cvery much a man of fashion in his person and demeanour, full of anecdote, and with a turn for satirical humour that rendered him a very amusing companion\u201d.<ref name = HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]]\n | years = 1774\u20131775\n | with  =  [[Thomas Fonnereau]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]]\n | years = 1780\u20131781\n | with  =  [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | after2 = [[James Marriott (judge)|Sir James Marriott]]\n}}{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Martyn Fonnereau]]\n | before2 = [[Richard Combe (MP)|Richard Combe]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]]\n | years = [[1780 British general election|1780]]\u2013[[1790 British general election|1790]]\n | with  =  [[Martyn Fonnereau]]\n| with2  =  [[Samuel Salt]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[George Grey, 6th Earl of Stamford|Lord Grey of Groby]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Grenville]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crespigny, Philip Champion}}\n[[Category:1730s births]]\n[[Category:1803 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Philip Champion de Crespigny''' (1738\u20131803) was a British lawyer and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1774 and 1790.\n \nHe was of [[Huguenot]] descent, the son of Philip Champion de Crespigny (1704-1765), [[proctor]] of the [[Admiralty court]], and his wife Anne Fonnereau, daughter of [[Claude Fonnereau]] of [[Christchurch Mansion]] in [[Ipswich]], [[Suffolk]]. His elder brother Claude was made a [[Champion de Crespigny baronets|baronet]] in 1805.\n\nPhilip Champion de Crespigny was probably educated at [[Eton College]] in 1748, and was an advocate of [[Doctors' Commons]] in 1759. In 1768 he became [[Government Legal Department|King\u2019s Proctor]] and held the post until 1784.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/crespigny-philip-champion-1803| title=\nCRESPIGNY, Philip Champion (d.1803), of Burwood, nr. Cobham, Surr.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1774 British general election|1774]] he was elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]] on the [[Thomas Fonnereau|Fonnereau]] interest after a contest, but lost his seat on petition. In [[1780 British general election|1780]] he was returned unopposed at [[Aldeburgh (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldeburgh]], also on the Fonnereau interest, as well as at Sudbury after a contest. He held both seats until 1781, when he lost Sudbury on petition, and continued to sit for Aldeburgh. The ''[[English Chronicle]]'' wrote in 1781 that \u201chis hauteur is so distinguished, that he is generally characterised ... by the profane, though very applicable appellation, of God Almighty\u201d. He was returned unopposed at Aldeburgh in [[1784 British general election|1784]], but did not stand in the [[1790 British general election|1790]] election.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nChampion de Crespigny was married four times: first, to Sarah, daughter of Thomas Cocksedge of [[Thetford]], [[Norfolk]], on 24 November 1762; second, about 1771 to Betsy Hodges who died 1772; third to Clarissa, daughter of James Brooke, on 1 July 1774 (she died on 15 May 1782); and fourth, to Dorothy, daughter of Richard Scott of [[Betton, Shropshire|Betton]], [[Shropshire]], on 20 February 1783. He died on 1 January 1803. His obituary in ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]'' described him as \u201cvery much a man of fashion in his person and demeanour, full of anecdote, and with a turn for satirical humour that rendered him a very amusing companion\u201d.<ref name = HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]]\n | years = 1774\u20131775\n | with  =  [[Thomas Fonnereau]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Walden Hanmer, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Walden Hanmer]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sudbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Sudbury]]\n | years = 1780\u20131781\n | with  =  [[Sir Patrick Blake, 1st Baronet|(Sir) Patrick Blake]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [